Bill of Rights (Amendments 1-27)
1st Amendment (1791): Protects the freedoms of speech, press, religion, assembly, and the right to petition the government.
2nd Amendment (1791): Affirms the right of individuals to keep and bear arms.
3rd Amendment (1791): Prohibits the quartering of soldiers in private homes without the homeowner's consent during peacetime.
4th Amendment (1791): Safeguards against unreasonable searches and seizures, requiring warrants to be judicially sanctioned and supported by probable cause.
5th Amendment (1791): Guarantees the right to due process of law; prohibits double jeopardy and self-incrimination; mandates compensation for private property taken for public use.
6th Amendment (1791): Ensures the right to a speedy and public trial by an impartial jury in criminal cases; guarantees the right to counsel and to confront witnesses.
7th Amendment (1791): Provides for the right to jury trials in civil cases where the value in controversy exceeds twenty dollars.
8th Amendment (1791): Prohibits excessive bail, excessive fines, and cruel and unusual punishment.
9th Amendment (1791): Clarifies that the enumeration of certain rights in the Constitution does not deny or disparage other rights retained by the people.
10th Amendment (1791): Affirms that powers not delegated to the federal government nor prohibited to the states are reserved for the states or the people.
- Subsequent Amendments -
11th Amendment (1795): Limits the ability of individuals to sue states in federal court.
12th Amendment (1804): Modifies the procedure for electing the President and Vice President, establishing separate ballots for each office.
13th Amendment (1865): Abolishes slavery and involuntary servitude, except as punishment for a crime.
14th Amendment (1868): Grants citizenship to all persons born or naturalized in the United States; provides equal protection under the law and due process rights.
15th Amendment (1870): Prohibits denying citizens the right to vote based on race, color, or previous condition of servitude.
16th Amendment (1913): Authorizes Congress to levy an income tax without apportioning it among the states based on population.
17th Amendment (1913): Establishes direct election of U.S. Senators by popular vote rather than by state legislatures.
18th Amendment (1919): Prohibits the manufacture, sale, and transportation of alcoholic beverages; initiates Prohibition.
19th Amendment (1920): Grants women the right to vote, prohibiting any U.S. citizen from being denied that right on the basis of sex.
20th Amendment (1933): Changes the commencement dates for congressional and presidential terms; commonly referred to as the "lame duck" amendment.
21st Amendment (1933): Repeals the 18th Amendment, thereby ending Prohibition and allowing for legal regulation of alcohol.
22nd Amendment (1951): Limits individuals to two elected terms as President of the United States.
23rd Amendment (1961): Grants residents of Washington D.C. electoral votes in presidential elections, treating D.C. as if it were a state for this purpose.
24th Amendment (1964): Prohibits poll taxes in federal elections, removing a financial barrier to voting.
25th Amendment (1967): Establishes procedures for presidential succession and addresses issues related to presidential disability.
26th Amendment (1971): Lowers the voting age to 18 years, ensuring that younger citizens can participate in elections.
27th Amendment (1992): Stipulates that any law varying congressional compensation shall not take effect until after an election of Representatives has intervened.
